I really hope it works out that way. It probably won't be a box office smash as the masses (and particular females) usually aren't really into space stuff, but who knows. This decade has graced us with Gravity, Interstellar, Blade Runner 2049 and now Ad Astra. Not a bad score. And we have Villeneuve's interpretation of 'Dune' in the works. text: I have a feeling that Tommy Lee Jones will be advertised as the film's villain, but it will be a marketing ploy, in order to hide the role of the true main antagonist, Donald Sutherland. Most movie villains these days are surprise villains, with their roles as villains being hidden until the film's release. They did it with Koba in Dawn of the Planet of the Apes, Ego in Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2, Mysterio in Spider-Man: Far From Home, and many more.  I don't know for definite, but I think there's a possibility that Tommy Lee Jones will be the advertised antagonist to hide Donald Sutherland's role as the true main antagonist. It's possible. He played a great villain as President Snow in The Hunger Games movies, and he has a menacing presence that he brings to a lot of his roles.

It kind of felt like Interstellar but on a more psycological level and through the perspective of a man who was born to be astronaut. It's so realistic in how it portraits the mental activity during such a trip and the perspective of Earth from space. I don't get why I just knew about it until today and watched it right away. It doesn't seem to get the credit it deserves. Great movie and wow Brad Pitt is still such a great actor, I feel like he never lost it the way he portrayed the Major and his relation with his father and how the authorities uses him. Just wow. Watch it if you love space movies, this is defnitely a gem worth a lot!
